      analysis: 'The rhetorical question does not seek an answer — it is a declaration of permanent guilt. "Great Neptune" — invoking the god of the sea itself — is hyperbole that reaches for the largest scale imaginable to capture the magnitude of the crime. The metaphor then reverses: it is not that the ocean is too small to clean his hands, but that his hands are so stained they would "the multitudinous seas incarnadine" — turn the entire ocean red. The inversion is devastating: he is not contaminated by the world; the world would be contaminated by him. "Multitudinous" and "incarnadine" are enormous Latinate polysyllables whose weight and strangeness mirror the psychological enormity of what he has done — words that require effort to pronounce, as if language itself strains under the guilt. This moment begins the blood motif that runs to the play\'s end, where Lady Macbeth scrubs her hands in a state of mental collapse.',
