      analysis: '"Murder sleep" personifies sleep as a second victim alongside Duncan, killed not by a dagger but by the act of committing murder itself. Sleep is one of the most loaded words in Shakespearean symbolism — it represents innocence, peace, restoration, and the natural cycle of life. In murdering Duncan, Macbeth has murdered his own capacity for the kind of unconscious peace that sleep requires. The phrase "innocent sleep" appears immediately after, making the personification explicit: sleep is morally characterised as innocent, which means Macbeth has committed an act against something pure. The word "murder" is deliberately chosen over "destroy" or "end" — it carries legal and moral weight, framing what has happened as a crime against nature itself. Sleep becomes one of the play\'s central motifs, tracking Macbeth\'s psychological disintegration: he will not sleep peacefully again, and Lady Macbeth\'s somnambulism in Act 5 inverts the motif — she achieves only a tortured, guilt-ridden simulacrum of sleep.',
