      analysis: 'The exclamation is raw and immediate — not rhetorical performance but a genuine cry of anguish at the irrevocability of what he has done. "Wake Duncan with thy knocking" is addressed to the unseen person knocking at the gate, but the prayer is impossible: Duncan cannot be woken. "I would thou couldst" is grammatically in the subjunctive mood — the mood of wishes and hypotheticals — marking the impossibility. Macbeth understands immediately and completely that there is no undoing this. The dramatic irony operates powerfully: the knocking at the gate is Macduff arriving to discover the murder, so the knocking that Macbeth wishes could resurrect Duncan is in fact the knocking of his own justice beginning to arrive. Porter\'s comic scene immediately after creates a structural contrast — normalcy and humour pressed against the most psychologically intense moment of the play, heightening the darkness by juxtaposition.',
