      devices: ['aside', 'dramatic_irony'],
      analysis: 'The accumulation — "King, Cawdor, Glamis, all" — piles up Macbeth\'s titles to emphasise the completeness of his power, but the word "all" at the end suggests saturation: he has everything, yet Banquo\'s aside strips the achievement of any value. "Play\'dst most foully" is a masterpiece of understatement — a compressed euphemism for murder, regicide, and treachery delivered in three words. The aside is dramatically essential: it reveals Banquo\'s true thoughts while establishing that he will not act on them, positioning him as the moral foil to Macbeth. They received identical prophecies; Banquo responds with suspicion and restraint, Macbeth with murder. This structural parallel makes Macbeth\'s choices appear as choices, not inevitabilities — destroying any reading that the witches "made" him do it. Banquo knows, suspects, and stays silent, which is its own form of moral compromise that Shakespeare does not quite let him escape.',
      context: 'Banquo was reputedly an ancestor of King James I — Shakespeare presents him as noble, honourable, and resistant to the temptation of the witches\' prophecy specifically to flatter the king. By making Banquo Macbeth\'s foil rather than his collaborator, Shakespeare argues that the prophecies were not determining — they were an opportunity that a morally strong person could decline. Banquo\'s murdered ghost returning to haunt Macbeth at the banquet is also symbolically precise: the man who could have been king and chose not to pursue it by corrupt means becomes the permanent image of what legitimate succession looks like.',
