      analysis: '"To be thus" (to be king) "is nothing" without security — the throne, stripped of safety, has no value. This is ambition consuming itself: the goal has been achieved and is immediately revealed as insufficient. The soliloquy marks the transformation from ambition to paranoia as the dominant psychology — Macbeth is no longer driven forward by desire but backward by fear. "Fears in Banquo stick deep" — the metaphor of something embedded, like a blade, suggests that fear has become physical and inextricable. The phrase "he chid the Sisters / When first they put the name of King upon me" reveals that Macbeth resents Banquo\'s moral clarity — Banquo challenged the witches where Macbeth accepted them. This is the soliloquy in which Macbeth decides to murder Banquo, and Shakespeare structures it to show that the decision emerges not from fresh ambition but from the corrosive anxiety that power without morality generates.',
      context: 'This soliloquy is the precise moment at which Macbeth\'s tragedy shifts its mechanism: in Acts 1\u20132, he was driven by ambition toward a goal; from Act 3 onward, he is driven by fear away from threats. The distinction matters psychologically — ambition is a forward motion toward something desired, while paranoia is a reactive motion against imagined dangers. Shakespeare shows that illegitimately acquired power is inherently unstable because it rests on no foundation of right, only on force — and force must be perpetually renewed. Every murder creates a new threat that requires another murder.',
