      devices: ['metaphor', 'soliloquy'],
      analysis: '"Full of scorpions" — the metaphor is viscerally uncomfortable: scorpions are venomous, numerous, and impossible to remove once they have invaded a space. Guilt has not arrived as a single wound but as an infestation. The plural "scorpions" matters: it is not one source of torment but many, suggesting that guilt has multiplied beyond the original crime and is now generative, producing new anxieties and torments with every moment. The inverted syntax — "full of scorpions is my mind" rather than "my mind is full of scorpions" — places the affliction first and the mind second, enacting the way guilt has come to precede and dominate his sense of self. "Dear wife" is the jarring counter-note: a term of tender intimacy delivered in the middle of psychological disintegration. The contrast between the domestic address and the horror of the confession is precisely the kind of tonal complexity that makes Shakespeare\'s characterisation so psychologically modern.',
